# === finding-adf666b2-2b5b-4f5e-a24a-e920794970c4 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:finding-adf666b2-2b5b-4f5e-a24a-e920794970c4> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-28T15:14:39.231906Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research AutoGen\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "a0468aff-ce34-42cc-aca1-e39a62e19fa8" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "semantic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-28T15:14:39.231707+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "I need write permission to save the file. Here is the complete research summary:\n\n---\n\n## AutoGen Framework — Research Findings\n\n### 1. Repository Stats\n\n| Property | microsoft/autogen | ag2ai/ag2 (fork) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stars | **56.3k** | 4.3k |\n| Forks | 8.5k | 568 |\n| License | MIT (code) / CC-BY-4.0 (docs) | Apache 2.0 |\n| Language | Python + .NET | Python |\n| PyPI | `autogen-agentchat`, `autogen-core` | `ag2`, `autogen`, `pyautogen` |\n\n---\n\n### 2. Community Split (November 2024) — 4 Lineages\n\n| Lineage | Repo | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Microsoft AutoGen 0.4** | `microsoft/autogen` main | Complete rewrite; actor model, async |\n| **AutoGen 0.2** (legacy) | `microsoft/autogen` 0.2 branch | Community-maintained; v0.2.38 |\n| **AG2** (community fork) | `ag2ai/ag2` | Chi Wang + Qingyun Wu; Apache 2.0; backward compat |\n| **Semantic Kernel** | `microsoft/semantic-kernel` | AutoGen 0.4 runtime embedded; enterprise path |\n\nOriginal creators **Chi Wang** and **Qingyun Wu** departed Microsoft on **Nov 13, 2024**, forked to AG2 for community governance with contributors from Google, IBM, Meta, Penn State, UW. The `autogen`/`pyautogen`/`ag2` PyPI packages all point to identical AG2 code — source of major developer confusion.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Core Agent Architecture (v0.2 / AG2)\n\n```\nConversableAgent (base — stateful, message-based, register_reply hooks)\n├── AssistantAgent    — LLM-backed, writes/reviews code, no required human input\n└── UserProxyAgent    — human proxy, auto-executes code blocks, solicits input\n```\n\n**GroupChat/GroupChatManager:** N agents, manager selects next speaker per round (LLM-driven, round-robin, FSM-constrained, or random). Speaker broadcasts to all other agents.\n\n**Conversation patterns:**\n- Two-agent (UserProxy ↔ Assistant)\n- Group chat (N agents, managed speaker selection)\n- Hierarchical / nested chats (sub-conversations within conversations)\n- FSM graphs (directed transition matrix for deterministic flows)\n- Swarm (AG2 addition: handoff-based agent routing)\n\n---\n\n### 4. AutoGen v0.4 Architecture — Actor Model\n\nThree-layer design:\n```\nExtensions (3rd-party, specialized)\nAgentChat   (simplified prototyping API, pre-built agents)\nCore        (actor model, async/event-driven messaging)\n```\nKey additions: OpenTelemetry observability, cross-language (Python + .NET), streaming, serialization, agent lifecycle management via runtime.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Code Execution\n\n| Executor | Description | Use Case |\n|---|---|---|\n| `LocalCommandLineCodeExecutor` | Subprocess on host | Dev/testing only |\n| `DockerCommandLineCodeExecutor` | Isolated container, explicit mounts | Production default (since Jan 2024) |\n\nWorkflow: LLM generates code block → extracted → written to temp file → executed → stdout returned as message → LLM iterates.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Tool Calling\n\n**v0.2:** Awkward two-agent registration — `register_for_llm()` on caller, `register_for_execution()` on executor.\n\n**v0.4:** Unified — `AssistantAgent(tools=[fn1, fn2])`. Built on OpenAI function-calling; LLM emits JSON tool-call → AutoGen executes → result injected into context.\n\n---\n\n### 7. Memory & State\n\n**Memory protocol:** `add` / `query` / `update_context` / `clear` / `close` — pluggable backends:\n- `ListMemory` (chronological)\n- `ChromaDBVectorMemory` (semantic search)\n- `RedisMemory` (distributed)\n- `Mem0Memory` (cloud persistent)\n\nRAG: two-phase (index embeddings → retrieve chunks → inject as system context).\n\n---\n\n### 8. AutoGen Studio\n\nLow-code web UI (EMNLP 2024 paper). Features: drag-and-drop workflow builder, visual config for agents/tools/models, playground for interactive testing, profiler (message count, token cost, tool success rates), JSON declarative spec, Python/CLI backend.\n\n---\n\n### 9. Strengths & Weaknesses\n\n**Strengths:** Best conversational flexibility, native human-in-the-loop, diverse topology support, LLM/tool agnostic, large community (56k stars), AutoGen Studio for non-devs, OpenTelemetry in v0.4.\n\n**Weaknesses:** v0.4 breaking changes still stabilizing, no DAG support (manual orchestration), conversational loops hard to trace vs. LangGraph graphs, PyPI fragmentation (5 packages), governance uncertainty from split, external store required for persistence.\n\n---\n\n### 10. acteon-swarm Context\n\n`swarm.toml` confirms `acteon` is this project's own framework (`http://127.0.0.1:8090`). AutoGen informs:\n- Message-based stateful agent pattern is proven\n- Docker-first code execution is the right default\n- Protocol-based memory abstraction (add/query/update_context) is worth adopting\n- v0.4's unified tool model is cleaner than v0.2's two-agent split\n- The Microsoft/AG2 governance split is a cautionary tale for open-source strategy\n\nResearch saved to `research/autogen.md` (pending write permission approval)." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "0.8"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "2f39add6-b6b0-4b59-9914-c0bf10d168e8" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "I need write permission to save the file. Here is the complete research summary:\n\n---\n\n## AutoGen Framework — Research Findings\n\n### 1. Repository Stats\n\n| Property | microsoft/autogen | ag2ai/ag2 (fork) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stars | **56.3k** | 4.3k |\n| Forks | 8.5k | 568 |\n| License | MIT (code) / CC-BY-4.0 (docs) | Apache 2.0 |\n| Language | Python + .NET | Python |\n| PyPI | `autogen-agentchat`, `autogen-core` | `ag2`, `autogen`, `pyautogen` |\n\n---\n\n### 2. Community Split (November 2024) — 4 Lineages\n\n| Lineage | Repo | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Microsoft AutoGen 0.4** | `microsoft/autogen` main | Complete rewrite; actor model, async |\n| **AutoGen 0.2** (legacy) | `microsoft/autogen` 0.2 branch | Community-maintained; v0.2.38 |\n| **AG2** (community fork) | `ag2ai/ag2` | Chi Wang + Qingyun Wu; Apache 2.0; backward compat |\n| **Semantic Kernel** | `microsoft/semantic-kernel` | AutoGen 0.4 runtime embedded; enterprise path |\n\nOriginal creators **Chi Wang** and **Qingyun Wu** departed Microsoft on **Nov 13, 2024**, forked to AG2 for community governance with contributors from Google, IBM, Meta, Penn State, UW. The `autogen`/`pyautogen`/`ag2` PyPI packages all point to identical AG2 code — source of major developer confusion.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Core Agent Architecture (v0.2 / AG2)\n\n```\nConversableAgent (base — stateful, message-based, register_reply hooks)\n├── AssistantAgent    — LLM-backed, writes/reviews code, no required human input\n└── UserProxyAgent    — human proxy, auto-executes code blocks, solicits input\n```\n\n**GroupChat/GroupChatManager:** N agents, manager selects next speaker per round (LLM-driven, round-robin, FSM-constrained, or random). Speaker broadcasts to all other agents.\n\n**Conversation patterns:**\n- Two-agent (UserProxy ↔ Assistant)\n- Group chat (N agents, managed speaker selection)\n- Hierarchical / nested chats (sub-conversations within conversations)\n- FSM graphs (directed transition matrix for deterministic flows)\n- Swarm (AG2 addition: handoff-based agent routing)\n\n---\n\n### 4. AutoGen v0.4 Architecture — Actor Model\n\nThree-layer design:\n```\nExtensions (3rd-party, specialized)\nAgentChat   (simplified prototyping API, pre-built agents)\nCore        (actor model, async/event-driven messaging)\n```\nKey additions: OpenTelemetry observability, cross-language (Python + .NET), streaming, serialization, agent lifecycle management via runtime.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Code Execution\n\n| Executor | Description | Use Case |\n|---|---|---|\n| `LocalCommandLineCodeExecutor` | Subprocess on host | Dev/testing only |\n| `DockerCommandLineCodeExecutor` | Isolated container, explicit mounts | Production default (since Jan 2024) |\n\nWorkflow: LLM generates code block → extracted → written to temp file → executed → stdout returned as message → LLM iterates.\n\n---\n\n### 6. Tool Calling\n\n**v0.2:** Awkward two-agent registration — `register_for_llm()` on caller, `register_for_execution()` on executor.\n\n**v0.4:** Unified — `AssistantAgent(tools=[fn1, fn2])`. Built on OpenAI function-calling; LLM emits JSON tool-call → AutoGen executes → result injected into context.\n\n---\n\n### 7. Memory & State\n\n**Memory protocol:** `add` / `query` / `update_context` / `clear` / `close` — pluggable backends:\n- `ListMemory` (chronological)\n- `ChromaDBVectorMemory` (semantic search)\n- `RedisMemory` (distributed)\n- `Mem0Memory` (cloud persistent)\n\nRAG: two-phase (index embeddings → retrieve chunks → inject as system context).\n\n---\n\n### 8. AutoGen Studio\n\nLow-code web UI (EMNLP 2024 paper). Features: drag-and-drop workflow builder, visual config for agents/tools/models, playground for interactive testing, profiler (message count, token cost, tool success rates), JSON declarative spec, Python/CLI backend.\n\n---\n\n### 9. Strengths & Weaknesses\n\n**Strengths:** Best conversational flexibility, native human-in-the-loop, diverse topology support, LLM/tool agnostic, large community (56k stars), AutoGen Studio for non-devs, OpenTelemetry in v0.4.\n\n**Weaknesses:** v0.4 breaking changes still stabilizing, no DAG support (manual orchestration), conversational loops hard to trace vs. LangGraph graphs, PyPI fragmentation (5 packages), governance uncertainty from split, external store required for persistence.\n\n---\n\n### 10. acteon-swarm Context\n\n`swarm.toml` confirms `acteon` is this project's own framework (`http://127.0.0.1:8090`). AutoGen informs:\n- Message-based stateful agent pattern is proven\n- Docker-first code execution is the right default\n- Protocol-based memory abstraction (add/query/update_context) is worth adopting\n- v0.4's unified tool model is cleaner than v0.2's two-agent split\n- The Microsoft/AG2 governance split is a cautionary tale for open-source strategy\n\nResearch saved to `research/autogen.md` (pending write permission approval)." ;
