# === finding-b9529d6c-3616-4df7-af02-b22ce245c54b ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:finding-b9529d6c-3616-4df7-af02-b22ce245c54b> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-28T15:12:42.188303Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research OpenAI Swarm\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "a0468aff-ce34-42cc-aca1-e39a62e19fa8" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "semantic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-28T15:12:42.188057+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "I now have enough data to compile a comprehensive summary. Let me write up the findings.\n\n---\n\n## OpenAI Swarm — Research Summary\n\n---\n\n### 1. GitHub Repository Stats\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Repo | `openai/swarm` |\n| Stars | **21,200+** |\n| Forks | **2,300+** |\n| Released | October 12, 2024 |\n| License | MIT (standard OpenAI OSS) |\n| Status | **Superseded** — replaced by OpenAI Agents SDK (March 2025) |\n| PyPI | Never published to PyPI; install directly from GitHub |\n\nThe README now carries a prominent notice: *\"Swarm is now replaced by the OpenAI Agents SDK… We recommend migrating to the Agents SDK for all production use cases.\"*\n\n---\n\n### 2. Core Concepts\n\n#### Agents\nAn `Agent` bundles three things:\n```python\nAgent(\n    name=\"Billing Support\",\n    model=\"gpt-4o\",\n    instructions=\"You handle billing questions...\",  # or callable(context_variables)->str\n    functions=[check_invoice, transfer_to_refunds],\n)\n```\n\n#### Handoffs\nA function returns an `Agent` object to hand off control. The loop detects this and switches active agents while preserving message history:\n```python\ndef transfer_to_refunds():\n    return refunds_agent          # returning Agent triggers handoff\n\ntriage_agent = Agent(functions=[transfer_to_refunds])\n```\n\n#### Routines\nNot a separate class — just the agent's `instructions` (system prompt) describing a sequence of steps. The LLM follows them as a natural-language program:\n```\n1. Ask for the order number.\n2. Look up the order.\n3. If damaged, transfer to refunds.\n4. Otherwise, thank the customer.\n```\n\n#### Context Variables\nA shared `dict` threaded through every function call and instruction:\n```python\ndef instructions(context_variables):\n    return f\"Help {context_variables['user_name']} with their account.\"\n\nclient.run(agent, messages, context_variables={\"user_name\": \"Alice\"})\n```\nFunctions declare `context_variables` as a parameter and Swarm auto-injects it. The `Result` return type can update them:\n```python\nreturn Result(value=\"Transferred\", agent=sales_agent, context_variables={\"dept\": \"sales\"})\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Design Philosophy\n\nSwarm is an **\"anti-framework\"** or **educational reference implementation** — intentionally thin:\n\n- The entire runtime fits in a single Python file\n- No decorators, no class inheritance for tools — plain Python functions\n- Functions are auto-converted to JSON Schema via type hints + docstrings\n- Client-side only; **no server state** between calls\n- Transparency over automation: developers see exactly when control transfers and what data moves\n\n> *\"In an era where AI frameworks often come loaded with features and complexity, Swarm takes a decidedly minimalist approach.\"*\n\nThe stated goals: **lightweight**, **highly controllable**, **easily testable**.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Agent Communication Model\n\n```\nUser message\n    → client.run(active_agent, messages, context_variables)\n        → LLM call with active_agent.instructions + active_agent.functions\n            → Tool call returned\n                → Execute Python function\n                    → If return value is Agent → switch active_agent\n                    → If return value is Result → update context_variables, optionally switch agent\n                    → If return value is str → append to messages\n        → Loop until no more tool calls\n    → Return Response(messages, agent, context_variables)\n```\n\nOnly **one agent is active at a time** — there is no parallel multi-agent execution in the base framework.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Tool System\n\n- Python functions are the only tool type\n- **Auto-schema**: type hints → JSON Schema parameter types; docstring → description\n- **Three valid return types**:\n  - `str` — plain result appended to conversation\n  - `Agent` — triggers handoff to that agent\n  - `Result` — structured object carrying value + optional new agent + updated context_variables\n- No decorator required; functions go directly in `agent.functions = [fn1, fn2]`\n\n---\n\n### 6. Intentional Omissions\n\nSwarm deliberately does **not** include:\n\n| Missing Feature | Rationale |\n|---|---|\n| Persistent state / memory | Must manage yourself or use external storage |\n| Thread management | No Assistants API integration |\n| Hosted retrieval (RAG) | Out of scope |\n| Parallel agent execution | Single-agent-in-control model only |\n| Group chats / pipelines | Available in CrewAI / AutoGen instead |\n| Orchestration graphs | LangGraph's territory |\n| Human-in-the-loop hooks | Must implement manually |\n| Production error handling / retries | Left to developers |\n\n---\n\n### 7. Relationship to Assistants API\n\nThese are **completely unrelated** architecturally:\n\n| Dimension | Swarm | Assistants API |\n|---|---|---|\n| API surface | Chat Completions | Assistants (different API) |\n| State | Client-side, stateless between calls | Server-hosted threads |\n| Memory | None built-in | Built-in retrieval + file search |\n| Agent naming | Named \"Agents\" for convenience | Named \"Assistants\" |\n| Purpose | Educational / prototyping | Production-ready |\n\nThe README explicitly states: *\"Swarm Agents are not related to Assistants in the Assistants API. They are named similarly for convenience.\"*\n\n---\n\n### 8. Community Reception & Forks\n\n- **Reception**: Widely praised as a great learning tool. Generated substantial community discussion on release (Oct 2024). Respected practitioners (Arize AI, VentureBeat, LabLab) analyzed it seriously.\n- **Criticism**: Not production-ready; stateless design imposes significant work on developers; single-agent-at-a-time limits parallelism.\n- **Notable forks/inspired projects**:\n  - **Agency Swarm** (`VRSEN/agency-swarm`) — extends patterns from Swarm into production-grade multi-agent apps\n  - **agent-swarm** (`desplega-ai/agent-swarm`) — applies Swarm-like patterns to coding agents in Docker\n  - **Swarms** (`kyegomez/swarms`) — enterprise-grade multi-agent framework, inspired by the concept but far more feature-rich\n\n---\n\n### 9. Strengths and Weaknesses\n\n**Strengths**\n- Minimal boilerplate — the fastest path to understanding multi-agent patterns\n- Fully transparent control flow — no magic\n- Easy to test (stateless + pure functions)\n- Auto JSON Schema from type hints eliminates schema boilerplate\n- Clean handoff model: return an Agent to transfer\n\n**Weaknesses**\n- No persistence — every call starts cold; developers manage all state\n- No parallel execution — one agent active at a time\n- Scalability: implicit agent relationships (via transfer functions) become hard to audit in large systems\n- Not on PyPI; no production maintenance\n- Never meant to be extended; built to be read and reimplemented\n\n---\n\n### 10. Influence on Other Frameworks\n\nSwarm's **biggest influence was conceptual** rather than code-level:\n\n1. **OpenAI Agents SDK** (March 2025) is its direct successor — same primitives (Agents, Handoffs, Context Variables) plus Guardrails, tracing/observability, and production reliability. The Agents SDK is explicitly called \"a production-ready evolution of Swarm.\"\n2. **The Orchestrating Agents cookbook** (which Swarm implements) crystallized the **routines + handoffs** pattern that other framework designers studied.\n3. It clarified the design space: LangGraph chose explicit graphs; CrewAI chose role-based crews; Swarm chose trust-the-LLM minimalism. Subsequent frameworks defined themselves partly in contrast to Swarm.\n\n---\n\n### 11. acteon-swarm\n\nNo public framework named **acteon-swarm** exists in indexed sources. However, the local repository contains a `swarm.toml` config file with an `[acteon]` section:\n\n```toml\n[acteon]\nendpoint = \"http://127.0.0.1:8090\"\nnamespace = \"swarm\"\n```\n\nThis references a **local/proprietary service** running at port 8090 under the `swarm` namespace — not a public framework. It appears to be part of the project being built in this repository, where \"acteon\" is the name of the local orchestration harness being researched/built.\n\n---\n\n### Key Takeaways for the Team\n\n1. **Swarm = the reference design**, not a production dependency. Study the patterns; don't ship the library.\n2. The two primitives (Agent + Handoff) are sufficient for most orchestration needs; complexity lives in the LLM's instructions, not the framework.\n3. **Context variables** are the canonical way to share cross-agent state without a database.\n4. Swarm's stateless design is a feature for testability but a burden at scale — the project's `swarm.toml` config suggests a stateful harness (acteon on port 8090) wraps or replaces this layer.\n5. For production work, the **OpenAI Agents SDK** is the maintained evolution; for understanding the ideas, read Swarm's source directly.\n\n---\n\nSources:\n- [openai/swarm GitHub](https://github.com/openai/swarm)\n- [Orchestrating Agents: Routines and Handoffs — OpenAI Cookbook](https://developers.openai.com/cookbook/examples/orchestrating_agents)\n- [Arize AI: Swarm Experimental Approach](https://arize.com/blog/swarm-openai-experimental-approach-to-multi-agent-systems/)\n- [nuvi: LangGraph vs CrewAI vs OpenAI Swarm](https://www.nuvi.dev/blog/ai-agent-framework-comparison-langgraph-crewai-openai-swarm)\n- [VentureBeat: Routines and Handoffs](https://venturebeat.com/ai/openais-swarm-ai-agent-framework-routines-and-handoffs)\n- [OpenAI Agents SDK](https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/)\n- [InfoQ: OpenAI Swarm Orchestration Release](https://www.infoq.com/news/2024/10/openai-swarm-orchestration/)\n- [Medium: Using the new OpenAI Agent SDK](https://medium.com/data-science-collective/using-the-new-openai-agent-sdk-d41c9c85f425)\n- [LabLab: Understanding OpenAI Swarm](https://lablab.ai/blog/understanding-openai-swarm-a-framework-for-multi-agent-systems)\n- [Galileo: OpenAI Swarm Framework Guide](https://galileo.ai/blog/openai-swarm-framework-multi-agents)" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "0.8"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "c6900965-a930-4a29-9af3-ffa510ee6937" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "I now have enough data to compile a comprehensive summary. Let me write up the findings.\n\n---\n\n## OpenAI Swarm — Research Summary\n\n---\n\n### 1. GitHub Repository Stats\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Repo | `openai/swarm` |\n| Stars | **21,200+** |\n| Forks | **2,300+** |\n| Released | October 12, 2024 |\n| License | MIT (standard OpenAI OSS) |\n| Status | **Superseded** — replaced by OpenAI Agents SDK (March 2025) |\n| PyPI | Never published to PyPI; install directly from GitHub |\n\nThe README now carries a prominent notice: *\"Swarm is now replaced by the OpenAI Agents SDK… We recommend migrating to the Agents SDK for all production use cases.\"*\n\n---\n\n### 2. Core Concepts\n\n#### Agents\nAn `Agent` bundles three things:\n```python\nAgent(\n    name=\"Billing Support\",\n    model=\"gpt-4o\",\n    instructions=\"You handle billing questions...\",  # or callable(context_variables)->str\n    functions=[check_invoice, transfer_to_refunds],\n)\n```\n\n#### Handoffs\nA function returns an `Agent` object to hand off control. The loop detects this and switches active agents while preserving message history:\n```python\ndef transfer_to_refunds():\n    return refunds_agent          # returning Agent triggers handoff\n\ntriage_agent = Agent(functions=[transfer_to_refunds])\n```\n\n#### Routines\nNot a separate class — just the agent's `instructions` (system prompt) describing a sequence of steps. The LLM follows them as a natural-language program:\n```\n1. Ask for the order number.\n2. Look up the order.\n3. If damaged, transfer to refunds.\n4. Otherwise, thank the customer.\n```\n\n#### Context Variables\nA shared `dict` threaded through every function call and instruction:\n```python\ndef instructions(context_variables):\n    return f\"Help {context_variables['user_name']} with their account.\"\n\nclient.run(agent, messages, context_variables={\"user_name\": \"Alice\"})\n```\nFunctions declare `context_variables` as a parameter and Swarm auto-injects it. The `Result` return type can update them:\n```python\nreturn Result(value=\"Transferred\", agent=sales_agent, context_variables={\"dept\": \"sales\"})\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Design Philosophy\n\nSwarm is an **\"anti-framework\"** or **educational reference implementation** — intentionally thin:\n\n- The entire runtime fits in a single Python file\n- No decorators, no class inheritance for tools — plain Python functions\n- Functions are auto-converted to JSON Schema via type hints + docstrings\n- Client-side only; **no server state** between calls\n- Transparency over automation: developers see exactly when control transfers and what data moves\n\n> *\"In an era where AI frameworks often come loaded with features and complexity, Swarm takes a decidedly minimalist approach.\"*\n\nThe stated goals: **lightweight**, **highly controllable**, **easily testable**.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Agent Communication Model\n\n```\nUser message\n    → client.run(active_agent, messages, context_variables)\n        → LLM call with active_agent.instructions + active_agent.functions\n            → Tool call returned\n                → Execute Python function\n                    → If return value is Agent → switch active_agent\n                    → If return value is Result → update context_variables, optionally switch agent\n                    → If return value is str → append to messages\n        → Loop until no more tool calls\n    → Return Response(messages, agent, context_variables)\n```\n\nOnly **one agent is active at a time** — there is no parallel multi-agent execution in the base framework.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Tool System\n\n- Python functions are the only tool type\n- **Auto-schema**: type hints → JSON Schema parameter types; docstring → description\n- **Three valid return types**:\n  - `str` — plain result appended to conversation\n  - `Agent` — triggers handoff to that agent\n  - `Result` — structured object carrying value + optional new agent + updated context_variables\n- No decorator required; functions go directly in `agent.functions = [fn1, fn2]`\n\n---\n\n### 6. Intentional Omissions\n\nSwarm deliberately does **not** include:\n\n| Missing Feature | Rationale |\n|---|---|\n| Persistent state / memory | Must manage yourself or use external storage |\n| Thread management | No Assistants API integration |\n| Hosted retrieval (RAG) | Out of scope |\n| Parallel agent execution | Single-agent-in-control model only |\n| Group chats / pipelines | Available in CrewAI / AutoGen instead |\n| Orchestration graphs | LangGraph's territory |\n| Human-in-the-loop hooks | Must implement manually |\n| Production error handling / retries | Left to developers |\n\n---\n\n### 7. Relationship to Assistants API\n\nThese are **completely unrelated** architecturally:\n\n| Dimension | Swarm | Assistants API |\n|---|---|---|\n| API surface | Chat Completions | Assistants (different API) |\n| State | Client-side, stateless between calls | Server-hosted threads |\n| Memory | None built-in | Built-in retrieval + file search |\n| Agent naming | Named \"Agents\" for convenience | Named \"Assistants\" |\n| Purpose | Educational / prototyping | Production-ready |\n\nThe README explicitly states: *\"Swarm Agents are not related to Assistants in the Assistants API. They are named similarly for convenience.\"*\n\n---\n\n### 8. Community Reception & Forks\n\n- **Reception**: Widely praised as a great learning tool. Generated substantial community discussion on release (Oct 2024). Respected practitioners (Arize AI, VentureBeat, LabLab) analyzed it seriously.\n- **Criticism**: Not production-ready; stateless design imposes significant work on developers; single-agent-at-a-time limits parallelism.\n- **Notable forks/inspired projects**:\n  - **Agency Swarm** (`VRSEN/agency-swarm`) — extends patterns from Swarm into production-grade multi-agent apps\n  - **agent-swarm** (`desplega-ai/agent-swarm`) — applies Swarm-like patterns to coding agents in Docker\n  - **Swarms** (`kyegomez/swarms`) — enterprise-grade multi-agent framework, inspired by the concept but far more feature-rich\n\n---\n\n### 9. Strengths and Weaknesses\n\n**Strengths**\n- Minimal boilerplate — the fastest path to understanding multi-agent patterns\n- Fully transparent control flow — no magic\n- Easy to test (stateless + pure functions)\n- Auto JSON Schema from type hints eliminates schema boilerplate\n- Clean handoff model: return an Agent to transfer\n\n**Weaknesses**\n- No persistence — every call starts cold; developers manage all state\n- No parallel execution — one agent active at a time\n- Scalability: implicit agent relationships (via transfer functions) become hard to audit in large systems\n- Not on PyPI; no production maintenance\n- Never meant to be extended; built to be read and reimplemented\n\n---\n\n### 10. Influence on Other Frameworks\n\nSwarm's **biggest influence was conceptual** rather than code-level:\n\n1. **OpenAI Agents SDK** (March 2025) is its direct successor — same primitives (Agents, Handoffs, Context Variables) plus Guardrails, tracing/observability, and production reliability. The Agents SDK is explicitly called \"a production-ready evolution of Swarm.\"\n2. **The Orchestrating Agents cookbook** (which Swarm implements) crystallized the **routines + handoffs** pattern that other framework designers studied.\n3. It clarified the design space: LangGraph chose explicit graphs; CrewAI chose role-based crews; Swarm chose trust-the-LLM minimalism. Subsequent frameworks defined themselves partly in contrast to Swarm.\n\n---\n\n### 11. acteon-swarm\n\nNo public framework named **acteon-swarm** exists in indexed sources. However, the local repository contains a `swarm.toml` config file with an `[acteon]` section:\n\n```toml\n[acteon]\nendpoint = \"http://127.0.0.1:8090\"\nnamespace = \"swarm\"\n```\n\nThis references a **local/proprietary service** running at port 8090 under the `swarm` namespace — not a public framework. It appears to be part of the project being built in this repository, where \"acteon\" is the name of the local orchestration harness being researched/built.\n\n---\n\n### Key Takeaways for the Team\n\n1. **Swarm = the reference design**, not a production dependency. Study the patterns; don't ship the library.\n2. The two primitives (Agent + Handoff) are sufficient for most orchestration needs; complexity lives in the LLM's instructions, not the framework.\n3. **Context variables** are the canonical way to share cross-agent state without a database.\n4. Swarm's stateless design is a feature for testability but a burden at scale — the project's `swarm.toml` config suggests a stateful harness (acteon on port 8090) wraps or replaces this layer.\n5. For production work, the **OpenAI Agents SDK** is the maintained evolution; for understanding the ideas, read Swarm's source directly.\n\n---\n\nSources:\n- [openai/swarm GitHub](https://github.com/openai/swarm)\n- [Orchestrating Agents: Routines and Handoffs — OpenAI Cookbook](https://developers.openai.com/cookbook/examples/orchestrating_agents)\n- [Arize AI: Swarm Experimental Approach](https://arize.com/blog/swarm-openai-experimental-approach-to-multi-agent-systems/)\n- [nuvi: LangGraph vs CrewAI vs OpenAI Swarm](https://www.nuvi.dev/blog/ai-agent-framework-comparison-langgraph-crewai-openai-swarm)\n- [VentureBeat: Routines and Handoffs](https://venturebeat.com/ai/openais-swarm-ai-agent-framework-routines-and-handoffs)\n- [OpenAI Agents SDK](https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/)\n- [InfoQ: OpenAI Swarm Orchestration Release](https://www.infoq.com/news/2024/10/openai-swarm-orchestration/)\n- [Medium: Using the new OpenAI Agent SDK](https://medium.com/data-science-collective/using-the-new-openai-agent-sdk-d41c9c85f425)\n- [LabLab: Understanding OpenAI Swarm](https://lablab.ai/blog/understanding-openai-swarm-a-framework-for-multi-agent-systems)\n- [Galileo: OpenAI Swarm Framework Guide](https://galileo.ai/blog/openai-swarm-framework-multi-agents)" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "I now have enough data to compile a comprehensive summary. Let me write up the findings.\n\n---\n\n## Op" ;
	a <https://schema.org/SemanticMemory> .


