# === finding-f6a8133f-9bf6-41fb-9e46-d1a8abb64568 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:finding-f6a8133f-9bf6-41fb-9e46-d1a8abb64568> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-28T15:12:49.005477Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research MetaGPT\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "a0468aff-ce34-42cc-aca1-e39a62e19fa8" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "semantic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-28T15:12:49.005272+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Now I have enough information for a comprehensive report. The `swarm.toml` reveals \"acteon\" is this very orchestration system running the research task — it's not a MetaGPT sub-project.\n\n---\n\n# MetaGPT: Deep Research Summary\n\n## 1. GitHub Repo Stats\n\n- **Repo**: originally `geekan/MetaGPT`, now moved to `FoundationAgents/MetaGPT`\n- **Stars**: ~66,400 (one of the most-starred agent frameworks on GitHub)\n- **License**: MIT\n- **Latest release**: v0.8.2 (March 2024 — maintenance patch); v0.8.0 was the last major release (March 2024), adding Data Interpreter and RAG integration\n- **Python requirement**: 3.9–3.11 (not 3.12+)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Core Concept: Software Company Simulation\n\nMetaGPT models an entire software company as a multi-agent system. Given a single natural-language requirement, it produces PRDs, competitive analysis, system design, code, and tests.\n\n**Core philosophy**: `Code = SOP(Team)`\n\nAgent roles (mapped to real company positions):\n| Role | Responsibility |\n|------|---------------|\n| Product Manager | Writes PRDs, user stories, competitive analysis |\n| Architect | System design, file structure, API specs |\n| Project Manager | Task decomposition, sprint planning |\n| Engineer | Code generation, unit test execution, debugging |\n| QA Engineer | Test planning, bug reporting |\n\n---\n\n## 3. SOP-Based Workflow\n\nStandard Operating Procedures are encoded directly into prompt sequences. Each role receives structured instructions defining exactly what inputs they consume, what outputs they must produce, and how to verify intermediate results. This is the key differentiator from chat-based frameworks like ChatDev — agents don't free-form chat; they follow explicit procedures.\n\nWorkflow phases: **Requirement → Design → Coding → Testing → Documentation**\n\n---\n\n## 4. Agent Communication Model\n\n**Shared Message Pool** (publish-subscribe):\n- Agents publish structured outputs (documents, specs, code) to a centralized pool\n- Each agent subscribes only to messages relevant to its role profile\n- No direct point-to-point dialogue — agents read from the pool asynchronously\n- Prevents \"cascading hallucinations\" caused by naively chaining LLM outputs\n\n**Structured artifacts** passed between roles:\n- Product Requirements Document (PRD)\n- System Design Specification\n- Task list / file list\n- Source code + unit tests\n\nThis is architecturally distinct from AutoGen (free-form chat) and LangGraph (graph-based state machine).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Tool and Action System\n\nEach **Role** contains a set of **Actions** (skills it can execute):\n- `WriteCode`, `RunCode`, `DebugError`, `WriteTest` — engineering actions\n- `WritePRD`, `WriteDesign` — product/architecture actions\n- Code execution loop: write → run → debug (up to 3 retries with executable feedback)\n\n**Data Interpreter** tool set (notebook-based agent):\n- Python notebook execution\n- Browser automation\n- Shell commands\n- Stable Diffusion image generation\n- Custom tool plugins\n\nTool selection uses a **relevance ranking** step: given a task description, the interpreter narrows candidates and selects top-k tools by compatibility scoring.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Memory Model\n\nMemory in MetaGPT is **role-scoped**: each agent maintains a list of messages (structured context objects) containing observations, outputs, and relevant shared-pool messages it has subscribed to. There is no global long-term memory store — context is local to each role's message history. Documents (PRDs, specs) serve as the primary durable shared state.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Research Paper & Academic Context\n\n**Paper**: *MetaGPT: Meta Programming for A Multi-Agent Collaborative Framework*  \n**Authors**: Sirui Hong, Mingchen Zhuge, Jiaqi Chen, et al. (incl. Jürgen Schmidhuber)  \n**Venue**: **ICLR 2024 Oral** (top-tier; presented as oral = top ~1–2% of submissions)  \n**arXiv**: [2308.00352](https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.00352)\n\n**Key benchmark results:**\n| Benchmark | Score |\n|-----------|-------|\n| HumanEval Pass@1 | 85.9% |\n| MBPP Pass@1 | 87.7% |\n| SoftwareDev executability | 3.75/4.0 (vs ChatDev: 2.25/4.0) |\n| Token efficiency | 124.3 tokens/line (vs ChatDev: 248.9) |\n| Human revisions needed | 0.83/task (vs ChatDev: 2.5) |\n\n**Core problem solved**: \"Logic inconsistencies due to cascading hallucinations caused by naively chaining LLMs.\"\n\n---\n\n## 8. Sub-Projects\n\n| Project | Description | Status |\n|---------|-------------|--------|\n| **Data Interpreter** | Autonomous data science agent with dynamic planning, hierarchical task graphs, tool integration, and executable feedback | Shipped in v0.8.0 (March 2024) |\n| **AFlow** | Automated agentic workflow generation via Monte Carlo tree search in workflow space | **ICLR 2025 Oral** (#2 in LLM-Agent category) |\n| **MGX (MetaGPT X)** | No-code natural-language product builder — \"world's first AI agent development team\" | Launched Feb 2025; #1 ProductHunt Week (Mar 2025) |\n| **ReCode** | Unifies planning and action via recursive code generation | FoundationAgents research |\n\nThe team has rebranded as **FoundationAgents** with a broader research agenda beyond just the software company simulation.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Strengths and Weaknesses\n\n**Strengths:**\n- Strong academic foundation (ICLR Oral, Schmidhuber lab pedigree)\n- Structured outputs dramatically reduce hallucination propagation\n- Best-in-class for end-to-end software project generation\n- Executable feedback loop (real code runs during generation)\n- Highly cited and widely studied framework\n\n**Weaknesses:**\n- **High LLM costs**: Multiple agents running in parallel → expensive with GPT-4 ($2/project is the happy path; complex projects more)\n- **Rigid pipeline**: SOP workflow is mostly linear — less flexible for interactive or iterative tasks\n- **Context loss**: Long workflows can lose shared context despite the message pool\n- **Prompt brittleness**: Poorly specified requirements cascade into broken artifacts\n- **Debugging opacity**: Hard to attribute failures to a specific agent in the chain\n- **Python version constraint**: 3.9–3.11 only\n- **Release cadence has slowed**: Last major release March 2024 — team energy has shifted to MGX product and AFlow research\n- **High learning curve**: Complex configuration, requires understanding of roles/SOPs to customize\n\n---\n\n## 10. Community Reception & Adoption\n\n- **66,400+ GitHub stars** — among the top 5 most-starred agent frameworks\n- Widely cited in academic literature comparing multi-agent frameworks\n- Active Discord community\n- MIT AI Agent Index includes MetaGPT as a reference framework\n- Compared favorably against ChatDev in all published benchmarks\n- MGX product hit #1 ProductHunt Product of the Week in March 2025\n- AFlow paper (ICLR 2025 Oral) shows continued research momentum\n- Commonly used in enterprise rapid-prototyping and research contexts\n\n---\n\n## 11. \"acteon-swarm\" Reference\n\n**No references found in MetaGPT** codebase or documentation. However, the local `swarm.toml` in this working directory references `acteon` as an orchestration endpoint (`http://127.0.0.1:8090`), suggesting **acteon is the name of the swarm orchestration system running this research task itself** — it is not a MetaGPT component or sub-project.\n\n---\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n| Dimension | Value |\n|-----------|-------|\n| Stars | ~66.4k |\n| License | MIT |\n| Language | Python 3.9–3.11 |\n| Communication | Publish-subscribe shared message pool |\n| Workflow style | Linear SOP pipeline |\n| Best for | End-to-end software project generation |\n| Avoid when | Need dynamic/interactive workflows, tight budget |\n| Academic paper | ICLR 2024 Oral |\n| Key sub-projects | Data Interpreter, AFlow, MGX |\n| Org | FoundationAgents (formerly geekan) |\n\nSources:\n- [GitHub - FoundationAgents/MetaGPT](https://github.com/FoundationAgents/MetaGPT)\n- [MetaGPT arXiv paper 2308.00352](https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.00352)\n- [ICLR 2024 Oral presentation](https://iclr.cc/virtual/2024/oral/19756)\n- [MetaGPT: Meta Programming (ICLR proceedings)](https://proceedings.iclr.cc/paper_files/paper/2024/file/6507b115562bb0a305f1958ccc87355a-Paper-Conference.pdf)\n- [AFlow - FoundationAgents/AFlow](https://github.com/FoundationAgents/AFlow)\n- [Data Interpreter - KDnuggets](https://www.kdnuggets.com/metagpt-data-interpreter-open-source-llm-based-data-solutions)\n- [MetaGPT Review 2025 - Sider AI](https://sider.ai/blog/ai-tools/metagpt-review-2025-is-mgx-the-no-code-ai-agent-builder-you-ve-been-waiting-for)\n- [IBM: What is MetaGPT](https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/metagpt)\n- [Framework Comparison - StableLearn](https://stable-learn.com/en/global-open-source-ai-agents-introduction-and-selection/)\n- [MetaGPT X - FoundationAgents](https://foundationagents.org/projects/metagpt-x/)" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "0.8"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "45b256e7-f09e-40ac-bafc-74121efa3ed2" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Now I have enough information for a comprehensive report. The `swarm.toml` reveals \"acteon\" is this very orchestration system running the research task — it's not a MetaGPT sub-project.\n\n---\n\n# MetaGPT: Deep Research Summary\n\n## 1. GitHub Repo Stats\n\n- **Repo**: originally `geekan/MetaGPT`, now moved to `FoundationAgents/MetaGPT`\n- **Stars**: ~66,400 (one of the most-starred agent frameworks on GitHub)\n- **License**: MIT\n- **Latest release**: v0.8.2 (March 2024 — maintenance patch); v0.8.0 was the last major release (March 2024), adding Data Interpreter and RAG integration\n- **Python requirement**: 3.9–3.11 (not 3.12+)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Core Concept: Software Company Simulation\n\nMetaGPT models an entire software company as a multi-agent system. Given a single natural-language requirement, it produces PRDs, competitive analysis, system design, code, and tests.\n\n**Core philosophy**: `Code = SOP(Team)`\n\nAgent roles (mapped to real company positions):\n| Role | Responsibility |\n|------|---------------|\n| Product Manager | Writes PRDs, user stories, competitive analysis |\n| Architect | System design, file structure, API specs |\n| Project Manager | Task decomposition, sprint planning |\n| Engineer | Code generation, unit test execution, debugging |\n| QA Engineer | Test planning, bug reporting |\n\n---\n\n## 3. SOP-Based Workflow\n\nStandard Operating Procedures are encoded directly into prompt sequences. Each role receives structured instructions defining exactly what inputs they consume, what outputs they must produce, and how to verify intermediate results. This is the key differentiator from chat-based frameworks like ChatDev — agents don't free-form chat; they follow explicit procedures.\n\nWorkflow phases: **Requirement → Design → Coding → Testing → Documentation**\n\n---\n\n## 4. Agent Communication Model\n\n**Shared Message Pool** (publish-subscribe):\n- Agents publish structured outputs (documents, specs, code) to a centralized pool\n- Each agent subscribes only to messages relevant to its role profile\n- No direct point-to-point dialogue — agents read from the pool asynchronously\n- Prevents \"cascading hallucinations\" caused by naively chaining LLM outputs\n\n**Structured artifacts** passed between roles:\n- Product Requirements Document (PRD)\n- System Design Specification\n- Task list / file list\n- Source code + unit tests\n\nThis is architecturally distinct from AutoGen (free-form chat) and LangGraph (graph-based state machine).\n\n---\n\n## 5. Tool and Action System\n\nEach **Role** contains a set of **Actions** (skills it can execute):\n- `WriteCode`, `RunCode`, `DebugError`, `WriteTest` — engineering actions\n- `WritePRD`, `WriteDesign` — product/architecture actions\n- Code execution loop: write → run → debug (up to 3 retries with executable feedback)\n\n**Data Interpreter** tool set (notebook-based agent):\n- Python notebook execution\n- Browser automation\n- Shell commands\n- Stable Diffusion image generation\n- Custom tool plugins\n\nTool selection uses a **relevance ranking** step: given a task description, the interpreter narrows candidates and selects top-k tools by compatibility scoring.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Memory Model\n\nMemory in MetaGPT is **role-scoped**: each agent maintains a list of messages (structured context objects) containing observations, outputs, and relevant shared-pool messages it has subscribed to. There is no global long-term memory store — context is local to each role's message history. Documents (PRDs, specs) serve as the primary durable shared state.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Research Paper & Academic Context\n\n**Paper**: *MetaGPT: Meta Programming for A Multi-Agent Collaborative Framework*  \n**Authors**: Sirui Hong, Mingchen Zhuge, Jiaqi Chen, et al. (incl. Jürgen Schmidhuber)  \n**Venue**: **ICLR 2024 Oral** (top-tier; presented as oral = top ~1–2% of submissions)  \n**arXiv**: [2308.00352](https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.00352)\n\n**Key benchmark results:**\n| Benchmark | Score |\n|-----------|-------|\n| HumanEval Pass@1 | 85.9% |\n| MBPP Pass@1 | 87.7% |\n| SoftwareDev executability | 3.75/4.0 (vs ChatDev: 2.25/4.0) |\n| Token efficiency | 124.3 tokens/line (vs ChatDev: 248.9) |\n| Human revisions needed | 0.83/task (vs ChatDev: 2.5) |\n\n**Core problem solved**: \"Logic inconsistencies due to cascading hallucinations caused by naively chaining LLMs.\"\n\n---\n\n## 8. Sub-Projects\n\n| Project | Description | Status |\n|---------|-------------|--------|\n| **Data Interpreter** | Autonomous data science agent with dynamic planning, hierarchical task graphs, tool integration, and executable feedback | Shipped in v0.8.0 (March 2024) |\n| **AFlow** | Automated agentic workflow generation via Monte Carlo tree search in workflow space | **ICLR 2025 Oral** (#2 in LLM-Agent category) |\n| **MGX (MetaGPT X)** | No-code natural-language product builder — \"world's first AI agent development team\" | Launched Feb 2025; #1 ProductHunt Week (Mar 2025) |\n| **ReCode** | Unifies planning and action via recursive code generation | FoundationAgents research |\n\nThe team has rebranded as **FoundationAgents** with a broader research agenda beyond just the software company simulation.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Strengths and Weaknesses\n\n**Strengths:**\n- Strong academic foundation (ICLR Oral, Schmidhuber lab pedigree)\n- Structured outputs dramatically reduce hallucination propagation\n- Best-in-class for end-to-end software project generation\n- Executable feedback loop (real code runs during generation)\n- Highly cited and widely studied framework\n\n**Weaknesses:**\n- **High LLM costs**: Multiple agents running in parallel → expensive with GPT-4 ($2/project is the happy path; complex projects more)\n- **Rigid pipeline**: SOP workflow is mostly linear — less flexible for interactive or iterative tasks\n- **Context loss**: Long workflows can lose shared context despite the message pool\n- **Prompt brittleness**: Poorly specified requirements cascade into broken artifacts\n- **Debugging opacity**: Hard to attribute failures to a specific agent in the chain\n- **Python version constraint**: 3.9–3.11 only\n- **Release cadence has slowed**: Last major release March 2024 — team energy has shifted to MGX product and AFlow research\n- **High learning curve**: Complex configuration, requires understanding of roles/SOPs to customize\n\n---\n\n## 10. Community Reception & Adoption\n\n- **66,400+ GitHub stars** — among the top 5 most-starred agent frameworks\n- Widely cited in academic literature comparing multi-agent frameworks\n- Active Discord community\n- MIT AI Agent Index includes MetaGPT as a reference framework\n- Compared favorably against ChatDev in all published benchmarks\n- MGX product hit #1 ProductHunt Product of the Week in March 2025\n- AFlow paper (ICLR 2025 Oral) shows continued research momentum\n- Commonly used in enterprise rapid-prototyping and research contexts\n\n---\n\n## 11. \"acteon-swarm\" Reference\n\n**No references found in MetaGPT** codebase or documentation. However, the local `swarm.toml` in this working directory references `acteon` as an orchestration endpoint (`http://127.0.0.1:8090`), suggesting **acteon is the name of the swarm orchestration system running this research task itself** — it is not a MetaGPT component or sub-project.\n\n---\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n| Dimension | Value |\n|-----------|-------|\n| Stars | ~66.4k |\n| License | MIT |\n| Language | Python 3.9–3.11 |\n| Communication | Publish-subscribe shared message pool |\n| Workflow style | Linear SOP pipeline |\n| Best for | End-to-end software project generation |\n| Avoid when | Need dynamic/interactive workflows, tight budget |\n| Academic paper | ICLR 2024 Oral |\n| Key sub-projects | Data Interpreter, AFlow, MGX |\n| Org | FoundationAgents (formerly geekan) |\n\nSources:\n- [GitHub - FoundationAgents/MetaGPT](https://github.com/FoundationAgents/MetaGPT)\n- [MetaGPT arXiv paper 2308.00352](https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.00352)\n- [ICLR 2024 Oral presentation](https://iclr.cc/virtual/2024/oral/19756)\n- [MetaGPT: Meta Programming (ICLR proceedings)](https://proceedings.iclr.cc/paper_files/paper/2024/file/6507b115562bb0a305f1958ccc87355a-Paper-Conference.pdf)\n- [AFlow - FoundationAgents/AFlow](https://github.com/FoundationAgents/AFlow)\n- [Data Interpreter - KDnuggets](https://www.kdnuggets.com/metagpt-data-interpreter-open-source-llm-based-data-solutions)\n- [MetaGPT Review 2025 - Sider AI](https://sider.ai/blog/ai-tools/metagpt-review-2025-is-mgx-the-no-code-ai-agent-builder-you-ve-been-waiting-for)\n- [IBM: What is MetaGPT](https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/metagpt)\n- [Framework Comparison - StableLearn](https://stable-learn.com/en/global-open-source-ai-agents-introduction-and-selection/)\n- [MetaGPT X - FoundationAgents](https://foundationagents.org/projects/metagpt-x/)" ;
