	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-28T15:14:18.822789+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Here is the complete research on PentAGI:\n\n---\n\n## PentAGI — Deep Research Summary\n\n### 1. GitHub Stats\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Repo | `vxcontrol/pentagi` |\n| Stars | **13,800** |\n| Forks | **1,700** |\n| Open Issues | ~15 |\n| License | MIT (Cloud SDK: AGPL-3.0 exception) |\n| Published | February 2026 (trended on GitHub immediately) |\n| Note | Source briefly restricted for license compliance audit |\n\n---\n\n### 2. Architecture\n\nPentAGI is a **containerized microservices platform** built around a custom multi-agent orchestration framework. Three-layer design:\n\n```\nUser / GraphQL / REST API\n        ↓\nPrimaryAgent (orchestrator)\nGenerator → Refiner → Plan\n        ↓\n┌──────────────────────────────────────┐\n│ Research   │ Development │ Execution  │\n│ Searcher   │ Coder       │ Pentester  │\n│ Enricher   │ Installer   │            │\n│ Adviser    │ Reflector   │            │\n└──────────────────────────────────────┘\n        ↓               ↓\n  pgvector (vector)  Neo4j/Graphiti (knowledge graph)\n        └────── PostgreSQL ──────┘\n```\n\nInfrastructure: Docker-in-Docker with 5 isolated networks, optional two-node deployment (API node + Worker node).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Agent Roles — All 13\n\n| Category | Agent | Role |\n|----------|-------|------|\n| Orchestration | `PrimaryAgent` | Task decomposition and delegation |\n| | `Generator` | Breaks objectives into subtasks |\n| | `Refiner` | Optimizes task definitions |\n| User-facing | `Assistant` | Interactive chat |\n| Advisory | `Adviser` | Recommends tool strategies |\n| | `Reflector` | Self-validates; corrects agents that drift from tool calls to prose |\n| Research | `Searcher` | OSINT, web queries |\n| | `Enricher` | Contextual data enrichment |\n| Development | `Coder` | Writes/debugs exploit scripts |\n| | `Installer` | Installs tools inside container |\n| Execution | `Pentester` | Runs nmap, metasploit, sqlmap etc. |\n| Utility | `Simple` / `SimpleJSON` | Fast responses / structured JSON output |\n\n**General agents** (broader tool access): Assistant, PrimaryAgent, Pentester, Coder, Installer\n**Limited agents** (narrow scope): Searcher, Enricher, Memorist, Generator, Reporter, Adviser, Reflector, Planner\n\n---\n\n### 4. Communication Model\n\n**Message chain pattern** — shared conversation history across agents:\n\n```\nHuman Message (task)\n  → AI Message (reasoning + tool calls)\n  → Tool Message (execution result)\n  → AI Message (next action)\n  → repeat...\n```\n\n- **FlowProvider** manages the `[]llms.MessageContent` chain internally\n- **GraphQL** for frontend real-time subscriptions (streaming progress)\n- **REST** for admin operations (Bearer token + SSL/TLS)\n- **ProviderController** assigns per-agent LLM configuration (model, temperature, token budget)\n- **Barrier functions** (`FinalyToolName`, `CodeResult`, `HackResult`) signal task completion to orchestrator\n\n---\n\n### 5. Tool Integration\n\n**Security tools (20+)**:\n- Scanning: `nmap`, `masscan`\n- Exploitation: `metasploit`, `msfconsole`\n- Web attacks: `sqlmap`\n- Credentials: `hashcat`, `hydra`\n- Container: `vxcontrol/kali-linux` (Kali image) or `debian:latest`\n\n**Search/OSINT APIs**: Tavily, Perplexity, DuckDuckGo, Google Custom Search, **Sploitus** (exploit DB), Searxng, Traversaal\n\n**FlowToolsExecutor categories**:\n\n| Category | Capability |\n|----------|-----------|\n| Terminal | Docker command execution |\n| File | Filesystem ops inside containers |\n| Browser | Web scraping via scraper service |\n| Memory | pgvector semantic search |\n| Search | External API queries |\n| Agent | Sub-agent delegation |\n| Graphiti | Knowledge graph ops |\n\n---\n\n### 6. Autonomous Decision-Making\n\nFully autonomous once task is defined. Flow:\n\n1. Generator decomposes objective into subtasks\n2. Heuristic prompts drive agents through pentest phases (endpoint discovery → input validation → exploit → report)\n3. Reflector corrects agents that produce prose instead of tool calls\n4. Chain summarization prevents context overflow on long engagements\n5. Knowledge graph and vector store inform each next step using prior findings\n\n**Web app phases**: endpoint discovery, path traversal, CSRF, XSS, SQLi, command injection, SSRF\n\n---\n\n### 7. Safety Controls & Scope Limitations\n\n| Control | Implementation |\n|---------|---------------|\n| Sandbox | Ephemeral Docker containers for all ops |\n| Network isolation | 5 Docker networks; proxy config available |\n| Host separation | Docker-in-Docker; no host filesystem access by default |\n| Auth | Bearer tokens + SSL/TLS on all APIs |\n| Monitoring (beta) | Automatic \"mentor intervention\" + pattern detection |\n| Manual override | Pause flow, inspect task/subtask, invoke agent functions, resume |\n| Two-node deploy | Separates API from worker to limit blast radius |\n\n**Hard limit**: Cannot bypass strong encryption or exploit systems without pre-existing vulnerabilities. It is an automation layer, not a zero-day generator.\n\n**Official ethical requirement**: \"Never point it at infrastructure you do not explicitly own or have written permission to test.\"\n\n---\n\n### 8. Memory & Findings Management\n\n**Dual knowledge architecture**:\n\n| System | Technology | What it stores |\n|--------|-----------|----------------|\n| Vector store | PostgreSQL + pgvector | Memories, code, guides, search results — semantic search |\n| Knowledge graph | Neo4j + Graphiti | Timestamped episodes, entity/relationship tracking, temporal reasoning |\n\nGraphiti's episode-based model lets agents reason about *when* findings were made and *how* they relate (network topology, vulnerability chains). Chain summarization handles context window overflow.\n\n---\n\n### 9. Strengths & Weaknesses\n\n**Strengths**\n- Model-agnostic: 10+ LLM providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, AWS Bedrock, Ollama, DeepSeek, GLM, Kimi, Qwen, OpenRouter, DeepInfra, custom)\n- Persistent cross-session learning via knowledge graph\n- True end-to-end autonomy — no manual stepping required\n- Kali Linux container + 20+ tools out of the box\n- CI/CD embeddable\n- Per-agent model optimization (different LLMs for reasoning vs. execution)\n\n**Weaknesses**\n- No platform-level scope enforcement — relies on user ethics\n- Human trust gap: acts as orchestrator, not co-pilot; hard to audit under real engagement scrutiny\n- Cannot exploit without a pre-existing vulnerability\n- Execution monitoring still in beta; flows can get stuck\n- Docker runtime required — no rootless/restricted env support\n- Despite 13.8k stars, community discussion is thin (~3 active threads)\n- MIT license with AGPL-3.0 cloud SDK carve-out adds licensing complexity\n\n---\n\n### 10. Community Reception\n\n- **13,800 stars, 1,700 forks** — strong initial surge; trended on GitHub Feb 2026\n- Sentiment: predominantly positive on GitHub and tech blogs\n- Security community criticism: dual-use concerns; preference for human-in-the-loop tools in actual engagements\n- Issue tracker: ~15 open — relatively clean for the project's scale\n- Discussion participation: modest; mostly consumers, not co-developers\n\n---\n\n### 11. acteon-swarm References\n\n**None found anywhere.** PentAGI uses its own custom orchestration (FlowProvider / FlowToolsExecutor). No references to acteon-swarm, CrewAI, AutoGen, or any third-party swarm framework appear in the repo, README, DeepWiki docs, or community discussions.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n- [GitHub - vxcontrol/pentagi](https://github.com/vxcontrol/pentagi)\n- [DeepWiki - vxcontrol/pentagi](https://deepwiki.com/vxcontrol/pentagi)\n- [DeepWiki - AI Agents detail](https://deepwiki.com/vxcontrol/pentagi/5-ai-agents)\n- [PentAGI Explained](https://hoangyell.com/pentagi-explained/)\n- [Cybersecurity News](https://cybersecuritynews.com/pentagi-penetration-testing-tool/)\n- [SitePoint - Security Patterns from PentAGI](https://www.sitepoint.com/security-patterns-for-autonomous-agents-lessons-from-pentagi/)\n- [PentAGI vs Penligent](https://www.penligent.ai/hackinglabs/pentagi-vs-penligent-what-security-teams-should-actually-compare-before-they-trust-an-ai-pentest-workflow/)\n- [AIToolly - GitHub trending](https://aitoolly.com/ai-news/article/2026-02-22-pentagi-autonomous-ai-agent-system-for-complex-penetration-testing-tasks-trending-on-github)\n- [Docker Hub](https://hub.docker.com/r/vxcontrol/pentagi)" ;
